          "body": "The chapter's interpretive audacity lies in its insistence that YHWH, not Nebuchadnezzar, is the chapter's primary actor. Verse 2 names YHWH as the one who sent the raiding bands — Chaldean, Aramean, Moabite, Ammonite. Verse 3 frames the entire enterprise as 'the command of the LORD.' Verse 13 notes that the looting of the temple happened 'just as the LORD had said.' Verse 20 closes with 'through the anger of the LORD this came about.' The Babylonian armies are real, their military superiority is acknowledged (24:7), and Nebuchadnezzar's personal involvement is noted (24:11). But the author refuses to allow geopolitics to be the final explanation. This is the same theological move Isaiah made when he called Assyria 'the rod of My anger' (Isaiah 10:5) and that Jeremiah made when he called Nebuchadnezzar YHWH's 'servant' (Jeremiah 25:9). Pagan empires operate within a sovereignty they do not recognize and cannot contain."
